The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (as it seems that it was Bercy who carried out the arbitrage) could have a double negative effect; once within the EU (why do the other member states continue to donate if it is enough to borrow?) and then in the negotiations, since the developing countries are not completely deceived...
The chapter of premature financing is only a small question for a relatively short time compared to the total number of discussions on the climate.
But the drop could be too much in the immense machinery of the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this will not be the case.
However, it is essential to learn its lesson from this first year of premature financing.
First and foremost, France could announce a change in its way of recording for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and balancing justice with the other countries of the European Union.
Above all, France could bring forward the discussions on the subject of disputes of long-term financing (another, decisive and currently discussed topic): the question of "reculability" or the type of booking of its loans does not escape.
France could change its position to be as progressive with regard to disputes as it is with other things.
Hope is therefore based on the new Environment Minister Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprising announcement about the fast-start of France and its vision of "recyclability" and the use of loans would inherently increase the international trust base necessary for further discussions.
Alarm - pesticides taken by children
A child of 10 years occupies 81 different chemical substances throughout the day, according to a study published this Wednesday by the Association of Générations Futures (former movement to protect the rights and respect of coming generations).
The association, which explains that their results "given the small number of analyzed samples do not reflect a statistically significant value, but rather an illustration character of the treated problem," had bought between July and September the food usually consumed within four foods consumed by about ten years with meals plus a snack in supermarkets in Oise and Paris.
These typical meals - including the official recommendations of five fresh fruit and fruit parts, three dairy products and 1.5 litres of water per day - were examined as well as sweets from laboratories in the search for chemical substances, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The plate balance is devastating: 81 chemical substances, including 42 classified as possibly or probably carcinogenic and five classified as safely barren, as well as 37 substances with an endocrinine disturbance factor, according to studies by several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Center.
"Even if the legal limits for each chemical, individually taken substance are not exceeded in the approximately settling, this survey is very well taken from the fact that the reality in which consumers are exposed to possibly carcinogenic substances or substances with an endocrin disturbance factor is caused by the consumer," the association notes.
Already at breakfast, the butter and tea with milk already contain more than ten of the potentially carcinogenic residues and three safely proven to be carcinogenic, as well as more than twenty residues that can affect the hormonal system.
The apple imported from Brazil, intended as a snack for the study, has traces of six chemical substances, including a fungicide banned in France.
The same goes for the green beans from Kenya, included in lunch, where the study has found traces of an insecticide that was strictly banned in the EU.
Furthermore, the hoe steak, the tuna from the can, even the baguette and the chewing gum of pesticides and other chemical substances were also peppered.
In the case of tap water, the analyses have brought the presence of nitrates and chloroform to light.
At dinner, the salmon steak was "rich in the most" with 34 chemical residues, and even the plastic plate used to warm up the meal in the microwave was not unencumbered.
The final risk of this "pollutant cocktail" for the consumer "will probably be undervalued," says the study.
For its part, the Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Verts (EE-LV) has proposed "given the urgency of the situation" to introduce a moratorium on the use of pesticides to stop the "increase in diseases of civilisation".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) identified the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables, which are consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
